107
00:06:45,782 --> 00:06:46,965
Rym: So, moving on with the news.

108
00:06:47,848 --> 00:06:52,040
Rym: We talked a lot about the new Mac Intel PCs coming out.

109
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:56,880
Rym: And now there's a lot of questions as to whether or not they're actually going to be able to run Windows.

110
00:06:57,641 --> 00:06:59,639
Rym: And the short answer is, no one knows.

111
00:07:00,520 --> 00:07:09,540
Scott: The story is, is that right now, PCs with, you know, normal Intel AMD processors, whatever, have a BIOS in them.

112
00:07:10,140 --> 00:07:11,279
Rym: Basic input/output system.

113
00:07:11,500 --> 00:07:11,820
Rym: Right.

114
00:07:11,921 --> 00:07:12,584
Rym: That's all that stuff.

115
00:07:12,604 --> 00:07:15,420
Rym: you see when the computer boots before Windows or Linux starts.

116
00:07:15,940 --> 00:07:17,735
Rym: You know, hit F1 and then there's all these options.

117
00:07:17,755 --> 00:07:18,400
Rym: you don't understand.

118
00:07:19,285 --> 00:07:20,058
Scott: That's all that stuff.

119
00:07:22,120 --> 00:07:24,608
Scott: Basically, Apple doesn't use BIOS.

120
00:07:24,728 --> 00:07:28,560
Scott: Apple uses Open Firmware, which is more advanced by far.

121
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:30,725
Scott: BIOS is really, really old and crappy.

122
00:07:30,826 --> 00:07:35,740
Scott: It's just so standard and old that we keep using it instead of switching to something new.

123
00:07:36,840 --> 00:07:41,220
Scott: There's something even newer called EFI, which is something Intel invented.

124
00:07:41,462 --> 00:07:43,240
Rym: Extensible Firmware Interface.

125
00:07:43,860 --> 00:07:44,283
Scott: Yeah.

126
00:07:44,303 --> 00:07:46,960
Scott: They invented that for those Itanium chips, actually.

127
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:49,740
Rym: Which is, isn't that what's in the MacTiles?

128
00:07:50,120 --> 00:07:52,688
Scott: That is what is in the MacBooks.

129
00:07:53,490 --> 00:07:56,600
Scott: That, with the Intel Duo whatever chips.

130
00:07:57,180 --> 00:08:02,540
Rym: Now this raises a big question because Windows Vista supposedly is going to support this just fine.

131
00:08:03,660 --> 00:08:05,729
Rym: But Windows XP 2000, 98, 311, not a chance.

132
00:08:08,921 --> 00:08:10,325
Scott: Nope, those do not support it.

133
00:08:10,405 --> 00:08:16,600
Scott: However, Windows XP 64-bit edition supposedly does support EFI.

134
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:22,600
Rym: Of course, that ray of hope is shattered immediately by the fact that these aren't 64-bit processors.

135
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:25,519
Scott: Yeah, the Intel Core Duo is not a 64-bit processor.

136
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:32,778
Scott: So, the question is, will somebody, will, you know, Windows 2000 XP might just work.

137
00:08:32,798 --> 00:08:33,400
Scott: We don't even know.

138
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:39,900
Scott: If they don't work, will somebody create some sort of patch or mod to make them work?

139
00:08:40,059 --> 00:08:42,128
Scott: I say probably yes, definitely.

140
00:08:42,148 --> 00:08:44,217
Scott: Will Linux work?

141
00:08:44,317 --> 00:08:45,040
Scott: Almost certainly.

142
00:08:47,862 --> 00:08:55,720
Scott: But it could be that you just can't run Windows 2000 XP and that you will need to have Windows Vista to run on these Apple Books.

143
00:08:55,840 --> 00:08:58,599
Rym: And keep in mind that it's not 100% that Windows Vista will work.

144
00:08:59,041 --> 00:09:10,680
Rym: Because Phil Schiller, the Apple guy who, the only one who responded to this so far, said that they don't sell or support Windows itself, but at the same time they're not preventing anyone specifically from using Windows.

145
00:09:11,260 --> 00:09:14,815
Rym: So they're not trying to keep Windows off, but they're not trying to make Windows work.

146
00:09:14,895 --> 00:09:15,819
Rym: They're just kind of ignoring it.

147
00:09:17,683 --> 00:09:25,800
Scott: Yeah, so basically it might work, and it's a pretty good bet that it will, but I wouldn't actually put any money down.

148
00:09:26,323 --> 00:09:29,140
Rym: See, I would kind of put money down because I point out two things.

149
00:09:29,380 --> 00:09:37,460
Rym: One, EFI, at least in its raw form, but no one knows if they're going to implement this on these specific boxes, can fully emulate BIOS.

150
00:09:38,522 --> 00:09:41,033
Scott: Oh, see I read something like that somewhere and I was a little confused.

151
00:09:41,234 --> 00:09:42,600
Scott: So it can emulate BIOS.

152
00:09:42,820 --> 00:09:43,061
Rym: Yes.

153
00:09:43,322 --> 00:09:48,381
Rym: However, we don't know if these will do it or if that emulated BIOS will work 100%.

154
00:09:48,381 --> 00:09:50,659
Rym: Because Windows relies on the BIOS more than you'd think.

155
00:09:52,241 --> 00:09:58,319
Rym: Two, the reason I'll bet that any Windows is going to work is that one, Grub works just fine with EFI.

156
00:09:59,920 --> 00:10:02,526
Rym: Two, Grub can boot Windows just fine.

157
00:10:03,948 --> 00:10:04,730
Rym: Case closed.

158
00:10:05,391 --> 00:10:08,177
Rym: Because once Windows boots, it's fine.

159
00:10:08,618 --> 00:10:09,560
Rym: It just has to boot.

160
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:10,502
Scott: Really?

161
00:10:10,523 --> 00:10:12,420
Scott: It doesn't use the BIOS after it boots?

162
00:10:13,181 --> 00:10:18,580
Rym: Not to the point, basically once you get it booted, as long as the hardware abstraction layer is okay, it's going to work.

163
00:10:19,742 --> 00:10:28,680
Rym: Now the question will be if the old versions of Windows include a hardware abstraction layer that can handle whatever proprietary bits might be in these MacTel boxes.

164
00:10:29,780 --> 00:10:31,029
Scott: Yeah, see that's my question.

165
00:10:31,049 --> 00:10:32,580
Scott: It's something no one seems to be addressing.

166
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:37,409
Scott: These Macbooks have things like the Express slot.

167
00:10:37,990 --> 00:10:42,040
Scott: They have things like the built-in on-motherboard Wi-Fi and USB.

168
00:10:43,181 --> 00:10:44,345
Scott: No, not USB, Bluetooth.

